## How to add a fixture

<!-- PROJECT: Fixtures are the matrix-honesty discipline's
fuel.  Real-world inputs from external contributors surface cells
the internal audit can't see (no fixture exercises them).  Make
this path low-friction. -->

Real-world `<input>` fixtures are how we discover the cells the
internal audit hasn't surfaced.  Submitting one is the highest-
leverage contribution shape.

### Step 1 — sanitise

Use the project's sanitisation helper.  `<If you have one, point
at it: e.g. `<package> sanitize -i my-input.txt -o sanitised.txt
--source-component <COMPONENT>`>`

The helper preserves structure (so the fixture exercises the same
parser paths your real input did) but redacts:
* `<sensitive identifier 1>`
* `<sensitive identifier 2>`
* `<...>`

Always run with `--dry-run` first to review the substitution table.

### Step 2 — verify the sanitised output round-trips

```sh
<package> verify -i sanitised.txt --component <COMPONENT>
```

If round-trip fails, the fixture has surfaced a real bug — file
that as a bug report (next section).

### Step 3 — submit

Open a fixture-submission issue using the
`fixture_submission.yml` template.  Attach the sanitised file
along with:
* Source `<COMPONENT>` + version
* Brief description of what makes this input interesting (specific
  grammar feature exercised, edge case, real production scenario)
* The substitution table from the `--dry-run` (if you're comfortable
  sharing it)

We will:
* Place the fixture under `tests/fixtures/<category>/<COMPONENT>/`
* Add a row to `tests/fixtures/<category>/RESULTS.md` with provenance
* Run it through the audit harness and triage any new variance cells

