## How to add a new `<COMPONENT>`

<!-- PROJECT: This is the heaviest contribution shape.  Walk the
contributor through it concretely.  In NetConfig adding a new codec
is a multi-week task; the walkthrough should be honest about the
scope. -->

Adding a `<COMPONENT>` means implementing the project's
`<COMPONENT> interface>` for an additional `<external entity>`.
Scope: `<typically N-M weeks of focused work for a thoughtful
implementation>`.

Read the authoring guide first:
[`<core>/<COMPONENT>s/README.md`](<core>/<COMPONENT>s/README.md).
That guide is the source of truth; this section is a roadmap.

### Step 1 — declare the `<COMPONENT>`

`<EXAMPLE: Drop a subpackage under <core>/<COMPONENT>s/<name>/.
Decorate the class with @register.  Auto-discovery picks it up at
startup.>`

### Step 2 — implement parse → `<CORE_ABSTRACTION>`

Walk the `<input format>` and populate `<CORE_ABSTRACTION>` fields.
Tier 1 first (the cross-`<COMPONENT>`-stable surface); leave Tier
2 / Tier 3 for follow-up commits.

### Step 3 — implement `<CORE_ABSTRACTION>` → render

The reverse direction.  Honest declaration: if a Tier-1 field
doesn't have an obvious render in this `<COMPONENT>`, declare it
`<unsupported>` in the capability matrix rather than silently
dropping.

### Step 4 — declare the capability matrix

Every xpath in `<CORE_ABSTRACTION>` gets a classification:
`Supported`, `Lossy`, or `Unsupported`.  This is the matrix-honesty
contract — be honest now, fix later.

### Step 5 — synthetic fixture

Hand-craft a minimal fixture under
`tests/fixtures/synthetic/<COMPONENT>/` exercising every parser
branch.  Round-trip stable.

### Step 6 — real fixture (if available)

Add at least one real-world fixture under
`tests/fixtures/real/<COMPONENT>/` (sanitised — see "How to add a
fixture" above).  This is the gate from `experimental` to
`best_effort`.

### Step 7 — wire into the audit harness

The cross-`<COMPONENT>` audit picks up the new `<COMPONENT>`
automatically; you'll need to add per-pair expectation YAMLs under
`tests/fixtures/<expectations>/` for each `(source, target)` pair
the new `<COMPONENT>` participates in.

### Step 8 — doc updates

Per the doc-sync checklist in `CLAUDE.md`:
* `<core>/<COMPONENT>s/README.md` — update the `<COMPONENT>` list
* `ARCHITECTURE.md` — if the `<COMPONENT>` introduces a new
  `<wire format / paradigm>`
* `docs/CAPABILITIES.md` — add the row + the per-`<COMPONENT>`
  capability table
* `CHANGELOG.md` — entry in `[Unreleased]`

