## Commit-message convention

Commits follow a rationale-first convention.  See
[`CHANGELOG.md`](CHANGELOG.md) for the worked examples.

The shape:

```
<short imperative title — 50 chars or under>

<2-4 sentences of rationale: WHY this change, what user-visible
problem it solves, what alternatives were considered.  The diff
already shows what changed; the message is where the reader learns
whether the change matters to them.>

<bullet list of concrete deltas if helpful: file paths, key
function names, test count delta, matrix-class delta>

<co-author trailer if AI agents helped>
```

Example:

```
Fix cisco_iosxe_cli routing-instances declared unsupported

The capability matrix declared /routing-instances/instance as
Unsupported with a "wire-up deferred" reason, but parse + render
had been shipping for months.  The cross-vendor expectation YAML
disposition was already correct; the codec's own declaration was
the lie.  6 regression-guard tests pin the corrected declaration
shape.

* netconfig/migration/codecs/cisco_iosxe_cli/codec.py — flip
  declaration from UnsupportedPath to LossyPath
* docs/CAPABILITIES.md — table row aligned with the corrected
  matrix
* tests/unit/migration/codecs/cisco_iosxe_cli/test_capability.py
  — 6 new regression-guard tests

Suite: 3229 → 3235 passed (+6 tests).  Matrix delta: CODEC_BUG
holds at 0.

Co-Authored-By: <agent attribution if applicable>
```

Bad commit message: `Fix bug`.

